We're going to work on doing the embedding of sui-rpc-store into the fullnode, leveraging a subset of the CFs in sui-rpc-store to replace the existing rpc_index.rs usage. raw chain data will not need to be written into sui-rpc-store in this configuration since the perpetual store will have that information. 

This is likely a large change so we're going to want to iterate on a plan before we begin executing. some things to consider:

- we will probably want to change the channel type that is used to send checkpoints from checkpoint executor to the subscription subsystem from an mpsc channel to a broadcast one. This lets checkpoint executor enqueue in a nonblocking fashion and we can have multiple subscribers. We'll use this to hook up checkpoint ingestion streaming into the writing side of the sui-rpc-store.
- We can probably trivially create an ingestion client impl by wrapping the perpetual store
- We want to introduce using this new db in parellel to the existing implementation so that we can adequetly test before we make a hard cut over. to do so we'll want to include a config flag in the fullnode config (it probably makes sense to put it next to the rpc.enable_indexing config flag) to opt in to using the new db. We can then flip this config (temporarily) in swarm builder to run all the existing rpc tests in sui-e2e-tests so that we don't need to add a new set of tests
- We'll want the behavior at startup to be more graceful than the existing rpc_index.rs impl. On startup we'll want to evaluate the available range in the perpetual store in comparison to the state of the sui-rpc-store. If our current watermarks are inside that range we don't need to do any blocking work on startup and can just open the DB and let the normal indexing process catch up normally. If the DB is uninitialized, or if our last written watermarks are behind the available range in the perpetual store, we'll need to do a restore process which will block the node from beginning to execute checkpoints. This way we can guarantee a clean restored state for the live object set based tables.
- If the db is initialized but our watermarks are outside of the available range, the db will have some data in it and so before we begin to do a restore we will need to drop all of the data in the column families. We may need to expose a new function in sui-consistent-store to be able to trigger that.
- When we do a restore, using the data in the perpetual store, when it completes the live object set tables will have their watermarks set to the current tip of chain checkpoint that the node know about. The other tables will either be deactivated (the data in them is already present in the perpetual store so we don't need it stored again in the rpc-store) or are "history" tables. For these other tables we'll want to set their watermark to the lowest available checkpoint that the node has all data for (checkpoint, transactions, effects, objects, etc) so that those tables can begin doing a backfill. (this is a new mode that we'll need to make sure works with the existing Synchronizer)
- We'll likely need to create a new type that wraps the perpetual store and rpc-store, much like the existing RestReadStore which does this for the existing rpc indexes.
- We'll need to also wire up this into the existing pruner that prunes the perpetual store so we may need some small refactoring to expose a prune method since we won't be able to use the pruner service we built (since we won't have raw chain data in the db to drive the pruning process)
- The available range that we expose will need to take into account the perpetual store's high and low watermarks (highest executed checkpoint and pruning marker) as well as the high and low watermark in the sui-rpc-store
